 Cordella rolled his eyes when asked about Netflix=E2=80=99s hyperbolic cla=
ims regarding the viewership for its Jake Paul-Mike Tyson match last Friday=
 evening=E2=80=9438 million concurrent streams in the States and a worldwid=
e audience of more than 60 million, making it =E2=80=9Cthe most-streamed sp=
orting event ever,=E2=80=9D according to a company press release. Netflix e=
ven declared the undercard fight between Katie Taylor and Amanda Serrano to=
 be =E2=80=9Cthe most-watched professional women=E2=80=99s sports event in =
U.S. history=E2=80=9D with an average-minute audience of 47 million viewers=
=2E If that=E2=80=99s accurate, the Taylor=
-Serrano fight would have achieved=20=
the fourth-largest TV audience of 2023, behind just Super Bowl LVII and the=
 two NFL conference
championship games.

Not surprisingly, in the higher calling of broadcast television, a professi=
on stocked with members of the sainthood, TV network sources started pourin=
g cold water on those numbers immediately. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re trying to=
 say that at 11 o=E2=80=99clock on a Friday night, a women=E2=80=99s boxing=
 match got 47 million viewers, greater than every NFL regular season game o=
f all time on broadcast TV?=E2=80=9D Cordella asked rhetorically. =E2=80=9C=
It=E2=80=99s hard to believe that=E2=80=99s the right number.=E2=80=9D

To be fair, Cordella had already had a long week by the time the question w=
as lobbed at him. On Tuesday night, Comcast leaked to the Journal that it w=
ould be spinning off its cable assets, minus Bravo, and that NBCU Media Gro=
up chairman Mark Lazarus would move over to become the C.E.O. of the spinco=
=2E Matt Strauss would be ascending=20=
to take over many of Laz=E2=80=99s respon=
sibilities as the leader of Peacock and NBC Sports. There was a lot going
down in Philly and at 30 Rock. Anyway, this is a long way of saying that Co=
rdella answered the question with an unusual level of candor, especially fo=
r a Comcast executive.

Internally, of course, these kinds of bitchfests aren=E2=80=99t uncommon in=
 the ongoing battle between defensive traditional mediacos and ambitious an=
d well-capitalized streamers, particularly as they compete for sports right=
s. Last month, sports business executives mocked Apple for declaring that L=
ionel Messi=E2=80=99s playoff debut was =E2=80=9Cthe most widely viewed spo=
rting event ever presented by Apple=E2=80=9D without disclosing the actual =
number. More than a year ago, linear TV network executives howled in protes=
t when Nielsen consented to incorporate some of Amazon=E2=80=99s own first-=
party data in its Thursday Night Football ratings=E2=80=94a concession that=
 many likened to allowing the world=E2=80=99s fourth-largest company to gen=
tly rig its own numbers. Their complaints were so obstreperous that Nielsen
and Amazon shelved the plan for a year.

You=E2=80=99ve got to feel for the TV guys, who are fighting at a disadvant=
age here. Of course, they=E2=80=99re frustrated by the platform companies=
=E2=80=99 ability to either disregard transparency or gerrymander the data.=
 But also, the TV networks have all played by the same rules, using Nielsen=
 since the =E2=80=9950s under the premise that a third-party source was req=
uired to validate the data that is the coin of the ad sales realm. Has thei=
r obedient example meant nothing? Sure, Netflix used a third-party company,=
 TVision, for its U.S. numbers, but it wasn=E2=80=99t Nielsen and the way i=
t counts viewers is different.

In their defense, the streamers steadfastly believe that Nielsen is inheren=
tly biased toward linear, and that their internal numbers are most accurate=
=2E Unfortunately, no one is incentiviz=
ed to standardize these measures, and=20=
instead the industry is deluged with emphatic and occasionally misleading p=
ress releases and handout
stories. (Credit where it=E2=80=99s due: While Netflix didn=E2=80=99t use N=
ielsen for its Tyson-Paul fight, it will use the ratings service for its tw=
o Christmas NFL games.)

Much more than ego is at stake here. As the incumbents and streamers compet=
e for both eyeballs and deal flow, especially in sports, the old-school lin=
ear guys truly fear that these self-reported numbers are tilting the scales=
 away from their favor. =E2=80=9CWhat we=E2=80=99re trying to figure out is=
 probably not the size of the audience, it=E2=80=99s how relative it is to =
everything else that we do,=E2=80=9D Cordella said this week. =E2=80=9CIf y=
ou=E2=80=99re a sports league, you=E2=80=99re like, do I want to put my con=
tent on this platform versus a broadcast network? What=E2=80=99s the differ=
ence in reach I=E2=80=99m really going to have? If you believe the numbers,=
 you=E2=80=99re going to say, Wow, I can get higher than an NFL game gets b=
y doing Netflix.=E2=80=9D

