:0;list-style-type:decimal"><li><i>A potential Cowboys flex</i>: There=E2=
=80=99s a reason that TV network executives spend the offseason lobbying th=
e NFL to get as many Cowboys games as possible on their schedule. Even in d=
own years, Dallas draws more viewers on average than any other team. This y=
ear=E2=80=99s squad has its own unique set of depressing issues: The =E2=80=
=99Boys are 3-7, their quarterback is out for the season, their coach appea=
rs ready for defenestration, etcetera. Nevertheless, Dallas has two primeti=
me games left on its schedule: a Week 14 <i>Monday Night Football</i> game =
against the Bengals, and a Week 16 <i>Sunday Night Football </i>tilt agains=
t the Bucs. The league isn=E2=80=99t going to switch the <i>MNF</i> game: E=
SPN is doing a <i>Simpsons</i> tie-in, and
the work that goes into producing that feed makes it impossible to flex out=
=2E But I=E2=80=99m told it=E2=80=99s <i>poss=
ible</i> that the Cowboys will b=
e switched out of <i>SNF</i>. Apparently, NBC execs wouldn=E2=80=99t be ver=
klempt over losing America=E2=80=99s Team. <br/><br/>Alas, it won=E2=80=99t=
 be easy replacing Dallas. Amazon=E2=80=99s <i>Thursday Night Football</i> =
also has a game (Browns-Bengals) with zero playoff implications, and the NF=
L would have to decide <i>by tomorrow</i>=E2=80=9428 days before kickoff=E2=
=80=94whether it wants to flex out of <i>that</i> game. Also, the pool of g=
ames that could anchor a primetime window is especially shallow that week. =
The NFL=E2=80=99s two highest-profile Week 16 games are on Saturday (Texans=
-Chiefs and Steelers-Ravens). The Lions-Bears and Eagles-Commanders games o=
n Fox are untouchable, thanks to the NFL rule ensuring that Fox and CBS kee=
p at least one of the two home-and-home games between division foes (Fox wi=
th the NFC teams; CBS with the AFC ones). If I had to guess, I think
Fox would protect its Vikings-Seahawks game, which would leave the Broncos-=
Chargers available to flex. The Chargers appear headed for a wild card, and=
 the Broncos are kind of on the periphery of the race. I wonder if lowly Da=
llas is actually a safer bet?</li><br/><li><i>What=E2=80=99s up with Golf C=
hannel?</i>: Like every other cable entity, the Golf Channel is shedding su=
bscribers, and now it=E2=80=99s being spun off by Comcast along with USA, S=
yfy, <i>et al</i>. But viewers shouldn=E2=80=99t notice a difference, at le=
ast in live event coverage, for <i>years</i> to come, since its current dea=
ls to carry PGA Tour and LPGA events run through 2030. As NBC Sports presid=
ent <b>Rick Cordella</b> said yesterday at <i>SBJ</i>=E2=80=99s Media Innov=
ators conference, =E2=80=9CThe partners that we have on cable assets like G=
olf Channel and USA=E2=80=94we=E2=80=99re going to fulfill every obligation=
 and every promise we made to them.=E2=80=9D  <br/><br/>Cordella also conce=
ded that Comcast=E2=80=99s decision to spin off those networks was a
=E2=80=9Cmicrocosm of our larger industry. =E2=80=A6 The cable assets, when=
 NBCU was first purchased by Comcast, were the crown jewel. Now, we are loo=
king at things a bit differently in this fragmented media world that we=E2=
=80=99re in.=E2=80=9D</li><br/><li><i>NFL blesses Ellison=E2=80=99s move</i=
>: I perked up this week when <b>Brian</b> <b>Rolapp</b>, the NFL=E2=80=99s=
 top business executive, revealed some NFL kremlinology at the <i>SBJ</i> c=
onference. In particular, Rolapp praised <b>David Ellison</b>=E2=80=99s Sky=
dance, which is in the process of acquiring Paramount Global with the assis=
tance of <b>Gerry Cardinale</b>=E2=80=99s RedBird Capital. Of course, Rolap=
p knows Ellison through the league=E2=80=99s collaboration with Skydance Sp=
orts, which produces <i>Hard Knocks</i>, among other I.P. =E2=80=9CThey=E2=
=80=99re smart,=E2=80=9D said Rolapp. =E2=80=9CThey=E2=80=99re certainly no=
w well-capitalized. They have a vision in leadership. And I think there=E2=
=80=99s a new sense of stability around that business, which will allow the=
m to innovate, which is exactly
what we want our partners to do.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>It=E2=80=99s not a surpr=
ise to hear well-compensated business leaders engage in the time-honored tr=
adition of log-rolling. But the industry remains infatuated with the NFL-CB=
S relationship, which was one of the key assets that made Paramount so attr=
active to Ellison and Gerry. Will the NFL stick to its full deal? Will it e=
xercise its option to reopen negotiations at the end of the decade? If it d=
oes the latter, will Paramount be able to <i>afford</i> the rights without =
Ellison pleading with his dad for a lifeline? <br/><br/>These questions rem=
ain unanswerable at the moment. But for now, at least, everyone is playing =
nice. Rolapp didn=E2=80=99t comment on whether the NFL will use a change-of=
-control provision to open up CBS=E2=80=99s media rights deal, but he made =
a point to say, =E2=80=9CWe want our partners to be stable and healthy and =
innovative, especially with the change that you=E2=80=99re going to see in =
the next 10 years. We expect and want that from
all of our partners.=E2=80=9D Meanwhile, let=E2=80=99s see what happens wit=
h those Netflix Christmas Day games=E2=80=A6</li><br/><li><i>An NFL Media n=
on-update update</i>: Three years ago, the NFL said it was looking for stra=
tegic partners to invest in NFL Media, the league-owned group that includes=
 the NFL Network, NFL RedZone, the NFL app, and NFL.com. The league has had=
 a bunch of talks since then, but Rolapp admitted that none of the suitors =
has met the NFL=E2=80=99s position. =E2=80=9CWe have not seen a plan that a=
chieves our reach, strategic, and financial objectives,=E2=80=9D he said. =
=E2=80=9CBut I think we will at some point. We=E2=80=99re fine with operati=
ng the way we operate it now. We=E2=80=99re in zero hurry.=E2=80=9D<br/><br=
/>Despite the inexorable decline of cable, Rolapp pointed out that NFL Medi=
a has grown its revenue and operating income every year. =E2=80=9CWe are no=
t distressed. It=E2=80=99s just the opposite,=E2=80=9D he said. He also tal=
ked about how NFL Media has changed how it produces content, focusing on th=
e studio show
<i>Good Morning Football</i>. The league was criticized when it moved produ=
ction of the show from New York to Los Angeles, which Rolapp says completel=
y misses the point. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s now a franchise we=E2=80=99re lea=
ning into that=E2=80=99s distributed on Roku,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CIt=
=E2=80=99s locally syndicated on broadcast stations, and it=E2=80=99s on th=
e NFL Network. We=E2=80=99ve just turned a franchise into one that has much=
 bigger reach and a bigger financial opportunity for us.=E2=80=9D</li><br/>=
<li><i>A =E2=80=98Varsity=E2=80=99 excerpt: Sara Fischer on Trump 2.0 and R=
