x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">So=E2=80=A6 do we b=
elieve the Tyson-Paul numbers? Skeptics have pointed to Nielsen=E2=80=99s S=
treaming Platform Ratings from that night. Per that report, <i>all</i> of N=
etflix averaged 25 million U.S. viewers on a per-minute basis last Friday i=
n the 8 p.m. ET to 1 a.m. ET window. It=E2=80=99s impossible to discern fro=
m the report how many of those 25 million people watched the boxing matches=
=2E (By comparison, in that same window=
 the previous Friday, Netflix averaged=
 11 million viewers across its entire service.) During the Taylor-Serrano f=
ight, the SPR report registered 25 million U.S. Netflix viewers. Its peak v=
iewership during that window was 28.2 million viewers in the U.S. <br/><br/=
>Obviously, it=E2=80=99s hard to square those numbers with those released b=
y Netflix. =E2=80=9CWhen they came out with such a big number, the whole in=
dustry attacked them and, I think, they looked
kind of ridiculous,=E2=80=9D one traditional media exec said. =E2=80=9CIf t=
hey had come out with a number around 25 million, that still would have bee=
n a huge win for them to claim.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>Netflix isn=E2=80=99t com=
menting beyond the releases it already put out. But it=E2=80=99s not alone =
in wanting to change the way the business counts streaming viewers. Last wi=
nter, using Nielsen, Peacock reported 23 million viewers, which stands as t=
he most streamed NFL game to date. But NBC sources said internal data showe=
d a higher number of viewers, which is a frequent complaint among streamers=
=2E Amazon, for example, consistently s=
ays that Nielsen underreports its NFL=20=
streaming numbers, too. Alas, one hallmark of this new era is that everyone=
 complains about Nielsen. Let=E2=80=99s see what happens, though, if the NF=
L Christmas games can=E2=80=99t outrate a women=E2=80=99s boxing match.<br/=
></td>
